{"cursor":"11331","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn analytic philosophy, the term 'anti-realism' is used to describe any position\ninvolving either the denial of an objective reality or the denial that verification-\ntranscendent statements are either true or false. This latter is sometimes\nexpressed by saying \"there is no fact of the matter as to whether or not P.\"\nThus, we may speak of anti-realism with respect to other minds, the past, the\nfuture, universals, mathematical entities (such as natural numbers), moral\ncategories, the material world, or even thought. The two construals are clearly\ndistinct and often confused. For example, an \"anti-realist\" who denies that\nother minds exist (i. e., a solipsist) is quite different from an \"anti-realist\"\nwho claims that there is no fact of the matter as to whether or not there are\nunobservable other minds (i. e., a logical behaviorist).\n","linknr":530,"url":"Anti-realism","recorded":1362580611,"links":29,"instances":["knowledge","metaphysics","philosopher","philosophy","philosophy","philosophy","philosophy_of_mathematics"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Realism","Epistemological theories","Metaphysical theories","Logical positivism","Metatheory of science","Metaphysics of science"],"headings":["Anti-realism in philosophy","Metaphysical Realism vis-à-vis Internal Realism","Anti-realism in science","Anti-realism in mathematics","See also","References","Bibliography","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/7/1/271fa8f6426e07d62848e8be6623e69f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/3/5/e358efa489f58062f10dd7316b65649e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/f/2/7f20aa0b3691b496aec21cf356f63e04.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg/20px-Wiki_letter_w_cropped.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/4/48/Folder_Hexagonal_Icon.svg/1